n'''Bradley Roberts Byrne''' (born February 16, 1955) is an American [[Commercial law|business attorney]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] congressman for [[Alabama's 1st congressional district]].  He served as chancellor of the Alabama [[Community College]] System from 2007 until his resignation in 2009 to run for the 2010 Republican nomination for [[Governor of Alabama]].<ref>[http://www.accs.cc/PDFs/News%20Release%20-%20Byrne%20Resigns-Board%20Appoints%20Interim%20Chancellor%20-%20052809.pdf ACCS Press Release: State Board of Education appoints Joan Davis as interim chancellor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100318170718/http://www.accs.cc/PDFs/News%20Release%20-%20Byrne%20Resigns-Board%20Appoints%20Interim%20Chancellor%20-%20052809.pdf |date=2010-03-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://byrneforalabama.com|title=Byrne for Alabama|access-date=February 23, 2010|author=|last=|first=|authorlink=|coauthors=|date=|year=|month=|format=|work=|publisher=|pages=|doi=|quote=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918235738/http://www.byrneforalabama.com/|archivedate=September 18, 2009|df=}}</ref>  He was also a member of the [[Alabama State Senate]] from 2003 to 2007. He holds a degree from [[Duke University]], where he was a member of the [[Phi Delta Theta]] Fraternity, and he also attended the [[University of Alabama]].<ref name=byrne1/> In December 2013, he won a special election to represent [[Alabama's 1st congressional district]] in the [[U.S. House of Representatives]].\n\n==Political background==\nByrne's first run for elective office was in 1994 was a success when he ran for the [[Alabama State Board of Education]] as a Democrat.<ref name=byrne1>{{cite news | first = | last = | authorlink = | author =Charles J. Dean | coauthors = | title =School Board Hopefuls Put Children First | type =newspaper | work =Birmingham News | publisher =Birmingham News | location =Birmingham, Alabama | id = | pages = | page = | date =October 9, 1994 | quote = }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news |author=Charles J. Dean |work=Birmingham News |publisher=Birmingham News| location=Birmingham, Alabama|title=Time of Change at State School Board Big Decisions Await Panel's Fresh Faces |page=101 |date=January 15, 1995}}</ref> During his term on the State Board of Education, Byrne supported a science curriculum that was opposed by many religious leaders in Alabama. He later voted with the Board to support a compromise that said, \"Explanations of the origin of life and major groups of plants and animals, including humans, shall be treated as theory and not as fact. When attempting to apply scientific knowledge to world problems, no social agenda shall be promoted.\" <ref name=\"Charles J. Dean 1A\">{{cite news |author=Charles J. Dean|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=Science Curriculum Gets Board Approval |page=1A |date =March 10, 1995}}</ref> In 1996 Byrne voted with the majority of Board members to reject $18 million in federal education funds because it was feared the money would allow greater federal control of schools. The vote was seen as a nod to the growing conservative influence in his south Alabama district.<ref name=\"Charles J. Dean 1A\"/> However Byrne later changed his mind and convinced the Board to allow the money.<ref>{{cite news |author=Tom Gordon|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=Education Board's Byrne Will Join GOP Today |page=1B |date =January 9, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997 Byrne left the  [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] party and became a Republican.<ref>{{cite news |author=Tom Gordon|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=Win Every Office in State Party Chairman Tells GOP |page=22A |date =January 12, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 Byrne ran for an Alabama State Senate seat, representing part of [[Baldwin County, Alabama|Baldwin County]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Gary Mitchell|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=SBOE's Byrne enters GOP Race for Lipscomb's Seat |page=State and Regional |date =January 16, 2002}}</ref> He won with 91% of the vote over his Democratic challenger.<ref>{{cite news |author=|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=Alabama Senate Results |page=News |date =November 7, 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Efforts against corruption==\nIn May 2007, Byrne took the position of community college chancellor <ref name=chanc>{{cite news |title=Byrne takes over |work=Mobile Register|location=Mobile, Alabama |page=B1 |author=George Altman|date=May 25, 2007|type=newspaper}}</ref> and oversaw a controversial reordering of much of the system. [[Bishop State Community College]] in Mobile was the target of investigators who found both financial and academic issues at the school in 2006 and 2007. Byrne ordered an audit of the school which demonstrated many deficiencies. At the time, about 2 dozen people were charged with criminal fraud and theft charges. A total of 27 would be charged before the probe ended in May 2007 <ref name=chanc/><ref>{{cite news | first = | last = | authorlink = | author =George R. Altman | coauthors = | title =Auditors: Bishop showing progress | type =newspaper | work =Mobile register | publisher =the Mobile Press register | location =Mobile, AL  | id = | pages = | page =B1 | date =September 12, 2008 | quote = }}</ref>\n\nByrne also worked with Alabama Attorney General [[Troy King]] to recover monies stolen from the community college system.<ref>{{cite news | first = | last = | authorlink = | author = | coauthors = | title =Attorney general King announces lawsuit to recover funds stolen by defendants in postsecondary corruption cases | url = | type =newspaper | work =US States News | publisher = | location = | id = | pages = | page = | date = | access-date = | quote = }}</ref>\n\n==2010 gubernatorial campaign==\n{{main|Alabama gubernatorial election, 2010}}\n\nDuring the campaign, he was accused by his opponents in the Republican primary of supporting [[evolution]] and of doubting that the Bible was [[biblical infallibility|infallible]].  \"As a Christian and as a public servant, I have never wavered in my belief that this world and everything in it is a masterpiece created by the hands of God ... As a member of the Alabama Board of Education, the record clearly shows that I fought to ensure the teaching of [[creationism]] in our school text books. Those who attack me have distorted, twisted and misrepresented my comments and are spewing utter lies to the people of this state.\"  He also added that he believed \"every single word\" of the Bible was true.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20004740-503544.html?tag=contentMain;contentBody | work=CBS News | title=Alabama Gov. Candidate Attacked for Belief in Evolution}}</ref>\n\n==Post-election activity==\nFollowing the run-off, Byrne went back to practicing business law, joining the Jones Walker law firm on August 16, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Bradley Byrne joins Jones Walker law firm |url=http://blog.al.com/businessnews/2010/08/bradley_byrne_joins_jones_walk.html |type=newspaper |publisher=[[AL.com]] |location = |date=August 16, 2010 |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n===Reform Alabama===\nOn February 23, 2011, Byrne announced he was partnering with other prominent Alabamians to create a [[nonprofit organization]] that would push for reforms in state government.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Despite losing GOP nomination for governor, Bradley Byrne still pressing for reforms |url=http://blog.al.com/breaking/2011/02/despite_losing_gop_nomination.html |newspaper=[[The Huntsville Times]] |location =[[Huntsville, AL]] |date=February 24, 2011 |access-date= }}</ref> Named \"Reform Alabama\", the organization actively supported legislation in the 2011 Alabama Regular Legislative Session.<ref>{{cite web |first= |last= |work= |publisher= |title=Reform Alabama Legislation |url=http://reformalabama.org/legislation |date= |access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Possible Supreme Court run===\nA May 25, 2011 ''Mobile Press-Register'' article reported that Byrne was considering the possibility of running for [[chief justice]] of the [[Alabama Supreme Court]] in the upcoming 2012 election. \"I\u2019ve been encouraged to look at it, and I\u2019m doing that. But I\u2019ve made no decision, and frankly I\u2019m no where near a decision at this point,\" Byrne said.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Alabama Supreme Court race has lawyers buzzing |url=http://blog.al.com/live/2011/05/alabama_supreme_court_race_has.html |newspaper=[[Mobile Press-Register]] |location=[[Mobile, AL]] |date=May 25, 2011 |access-date= }}</ref> He ultimately did not enter the race.\n\n==United States House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2013 special election====\n{{See also|Alabama's 1st congressional district special election, 2013}}\nOn May 23, 2013, [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Jo Bonner]] announced that he would resign, effective on August 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite news |first=George |last=Talbot |title=Rep. Jo Bonner resignation stuns constituents, sparks candidates |url=http://blog.al.com/wire/2013/05/rep_jo_bonner_resignation_stun.html |publisher=[[AL.com]] |date=May 23, 2013 |access-date=May 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nByrne finished first in the Republican primary\u2014the real contest in this heavily Republican district\u2014and faced Tea Party candidate Dean Young in the runoff election. Byrne won the runoff, but Young refused to endorse him,{{why|date=June 2018}} which led to rumors of a rift within the Republican Party. But Byrne subsequently gained the endorsement of Alabama Patriots, a Tea Party affiliated organization.<ref>{{cite news |first=Brendan |last=Kirby |title=Tea party group backs Byrne for Congress, disputes notion of rift in GOP |url=http://blog.al.com/live/2013/11/tea_party_group_back_byrne_for.html |newspaper=[[Mobile Press-Register]] |publisher=Alabama Media Group |date=November 12, 2013 |access-date=November 12, 2013 }}</ref> Byrne won the Republican nomination for the congressional seat and faced Democratic Party nominee Burton LeFlore on December 17, 2013.<ref name=sawyer2013>{{cite news | first = | last = | authorlink = | author =Jessica Sawyer | coauthors = | title =Byrne wins, Young concedes in Alabama-01 Republican runoff | url =http://blog.al.com/live/2013/11/polls_close_at_7_pm_for_al-01.html | format =Digital | work =AL.com | publisher =Alabama Media Group, LLC | location = | id = | pages = | page = | date =November 5, 2013 | access-date =November 6, 2013 | quote = }}</ref><ref name=\"wapo131217\">{{cite news |first=Sean |last=Sullivan |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |location=[[Washington, DC]] |title=Republican Bradley Byrne wins Alabama special election |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/12/17/republican-bradley-byrne-wins-alabama-special-election/ |date=December 17, 2013 |access-date=December 18, 2013}}</ref> Byrne won the election with 71% of the vote.<ref name=\"wapo131217\"/> He is only the sixth person to represent this Mobile-based district since 1919, and continues an unbroken run of Republican control in the district dating to 1965.\n\n====2014====\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Alabama, 2014#District 1}}\nByrne was originally believed to be running for re-election unopposed, but Burton LeFlore, his Democratic opponent in the 2013 special election, managed to qualify.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc3340.com/story/24668112/list-of-candidates-for-major-alabama-offices|title=List of candidates for major Alabama offices|work=ABC 3340|date=February 8, 2014|access-date=February 11, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213075548/http://www.abc3340.com/story/24668112/list-of-candidates-for-major-alabama-offices|archivedate=February 13, 2014|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"aldemocrats1\">{{cite web|work=Alabama Democratic Party|url=http://aldemocrats.org/blog/candidate_qualifying_ends_feb._7|title=Alabama Democrats|access-date=February 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nByrne won re-election with 68% of the vote.<ref name=generalresults>{{cite web |url=http://alabamavotes.gov/downloads/election/2014/general/2014GeneralResults-WithWriteIn.pdf |title=Certified General Election Results |publisher=Alabama Secretary of State|access-date=February 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nByrne supported the [[Faithful Execution of the Law Act of 2014 (H.R. 3973; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of Justice]] to report to the [[United States Congress]] whenever any [[List of United States federal agencies|federal agency]] refrains from enforcing laws or regulations for any reason.<ref name=3973cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3973 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45177|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|access-date=11 March 2014}}</ref> In the report, the government would have to explain why it had decided not to enforce that law.<ref name=HtargetsObamalawEnf>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House targets Obama's law enforcement|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/government-oversight/200167-house-to-attack-obamas-non-enforcement-next-week|access-date=12 March 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=7 March 2014}}</ref> Byrne spoke out in favor of the bill saying, \"the Obama Administration has been open and honest about one thing in particular: they have no problem making an end-run around Congress to achieve through administrative means what they cannot legislatively. Placing political convenience above the United States Constitution goes against everything the Founding Fathers intended, and it's time we put a stop to this practice.\"<ref name=ALpolRep>{{cite news|last=Moseley|first=Brandon|title=Byrne Co-Sponsors Act to Stop Selective Enforcement of the Law By Obama|url=http://alreporter.com/in-case-you-missed-it-2/5814-byrne-co-sponsors-act-to-stop-selective-enforcement-of-the-law-by-obama.html|access-date=12 March 2014|newspaper=Alabama Political Reporter|date=12 February 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207232937/http://alreporter.com/in-case-you-missed-it-2/5814-byrne-co-sponsors-act-to-stop-selective-enforcement-of-the-law-by-obama.html|archivedate=7 December 2014|df=}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nByrne has sponsored two bills of his own:<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Byrne's Legislation|url=https://www.congress.gov/member/bradley-byrne/2197?q=%7B%22sponsorship%22%3A%22sponsored%22%2C%22type%22%3A%22bills%22%7D|publisher=Library of Congress|access-date=December 4, 2014}}</ref>\n* H.R. 4465, a bill to set catch limits for the Gulf of Mexico [[Northern red snapper|red snapper]] fishery, introduced April 10, 2014\n* H.R. 5510, a bill to require recognized accrediting agencies or associations that evaluate the quality of distance or correspondence education programs to require those programs to have a secure login and passcode for Internet coursework, introduced September 17, 2014\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Armed Services Committee]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower & Projection Forces]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|House Education and Workforce Committee]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Rules|House Rules Committee]]'''\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=|date=|access-date=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nByrne is a member of the [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political stances==\n===National security===\nByrne supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to impose a temporary ban on entry to the U.S. to citizens of seven Muslim-majority countries. He stated that \u201cI appreciate President Trump\u2019s efforts to address these issues as he works to keep the American people safe. While there have been some issues with the order\u2019s implementation, I look forward to working with the Trump Administration to make sure their efforts to protect the American people succeed in a timely and effective manner.\u201d<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump\u2019s travel ban; here\u2019s where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban/|website=Denver Post|access-date=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Roy Moore endorsement===\nDuring the 2017 Alabama special election to replace [[Jeff Sessions]], who was appointed by President Donald Trump to the position of Attorney General of the United States, Bradley Byrne endorsed the Republican nominee, Roy Moore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/news/huntsville/index.ssf/2017/10/roy_moore_gets_endorsements_fr.html|title=Roy Moore gets endorsements from Alabama Republicans in Congress|website=Al.com|access-date=November 16, 2017}}</ref> During the campaign at least nine women made allegations that Roy Moore had either sexually assaulted them or made inappropriate romantic or sexual advances towards them while he was an assistant DA and the girls were teenagers as young as 14 or he was a lawyer and the women were clients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/15/us/roy-moore-alabama-republicans.html|title=4 More Women Accuse Roy Moore of Misconduct|first=Alan|last=Blinder|date=November 15, 2017|publisher=|access-date=November 18, 2017|via=www.NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/woman-says-roy-moore-initiated-sexual-encounter-when-she-was-14-he-was-32/2017/11/09/1f495878-c293-11e7-afe9-4f60b5a6c4a0_story.html|title=Woman says Roy Moore initiated sexual encounter when she was 14, he was 32|first1=Stephanie|last1=McCrummen|first2=Beth|last2=Reinhard|first3=Alice|last3=Crites|date=November 9, 2017|publisher=|access-date=November 16, 2017|via=www.WashingtonPost.com}}</ref> Following the original allegations of sexual impropriety, additional allegations were made including attempted rape of a 16-year-old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/13/us/politics/roy-moore-alabama-senate.html|title=Roy Moore Is Accused of Sexual Misconduct by a Fifth Woman|first1=Jonathan|last1=Martin|first2=Sheryl Gay|last2=Stolberg|date=November 13, 2017|publisher=|access-date=November 16, 2017|via=www.NYTimes.com}}</ref> Moore denied the allegations and his campaign and supporters began a process of questioning the victims' motives and veracity and claimed they would mount an \"investigation\" of the women's motives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/11/13/politics/roy-moore-washington-post-lawsuit/index.html|title=Moore threatens to sue Washington Post over report|first=Susannah Cullinane,|last=CNN|website=CNN.com|access-date=November 16, 2017}}</ref> Immediately following the allegations and instances of victim intimidation, numerous Republicans withdrew endorsements of Moore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1126733/roy-moore-heres-how-republicans-are-responding-to-the-allegations/|title=Here\u2019s how Republicans are responding to the allegations against Roy Moore|first=Annalisa|last=Merelli|website=QZ.com|access-date=November 16, 2017}}</ref> Byrne's endorsement of Moore was not withdrawn and no condemnation was made by Byrne of the victim intimidation threats made by Moore and the Moore campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/11/which_politicians_still_suppor.html|title=Which GOP politicians still support Roy Moore? Who withdrew endorsements?|website=Al.com|access-date=November 16, 2017}}</ref> On November 15, 2017, Byrne stated that \"I have no reason to doubt the stories that have been told [by the victims]\" but did not rescind his endorsement or call on Judge Moore to drop out of the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/video/lawmaker-interviews/360352-watch-gop-alabama-rep-no-reason-to-doubt-moores-accusers|title=WATCH: GOP Alabama rep: 'No reason to doubt' Moore\u2019s accusers|first=Molly K.|last=Hooper|date=November 14, 2017|website=TheHill.com|access-date=November 18, 2017}}</ref> On November 16, Byrne was given the opportunity to withdraw his endorsement of Roy Moore but he neither withdrew his endorsement nor condemned Moore's attack on his victim noting that it was Byrne's belief that it was up to the citizens of Alabama to make a decision about whom they should vote for.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/news/mobile/index.ssf/2017/11/bradley_byrne_roy_moore_is_the.html|title=Bradley Byrne: Roy Moore is the voters' decision, not mine|website=Al.com|access-date=November 18, 2017}}</ref> In response to Byrne's continuing support of Judge Moore in the face of 9 accusers, on 28NOV17 the statewide newspaper group in Alabama (Al.com) began running editorial cartoons titled \"I am Roy Moore\" with a picture of Bradley Byrne and a statement saying \"You condone it you own it.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/opinion/index.ssf/2017/11/i_am_roy_moore_us_rep_bradley.html|title=I am Roy Moore: U.S. Rep. Bradley Byrne|work=AL.com|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAfter Moore's loss to Democrat [[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]], Byrne hinted that he may run in the next regular election in 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/news/mobile/index.ssf/2017/12/after_doug_jones_win_bradley_b.html|title=After Doug Jones win, Bradley Byrne hints at 2020 Senate run|work=AL.com|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Tax reform ===\n\nByrne voted for the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar122117\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=21 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> During the bill's debate, Byrne stated that \u201cIt will lead to greater economic growth, higher wages, and more jobs, which is exactly what the American people sent President Trump and the Republican Congress to Washington to do.\"<ref name=\"Kirby122017\">{{cite web|last1=Kirby|first1=Brendan|title=Tax cuts will create 4,600 Alabama jobs, raise family income across the state by $519, study says - Yellowhammer News|url=http://yellowhammernews.com/featured/tax-cut-impact-alabama/|website=Yellowhammer News|accessdate=21 December 2017|date=20 December 2017}}</ref> Byrne voted for the bill believing it will lower taxes for all Americans and that it will \"pump up wage growth and that'll help wage growth.\" He said that individual incomes will increase as a result of the legislation.<ref name=\"Turley121617\">{{cite web|last1=Turley|first1=Kendra|title=Mixed reaction to revised GOP tax reform bill|url=http://www.fox10tv.com/story/37082827/mixed-reaction-to-revised-gop-tax-reform-bill|website=Fox10|accessdate=21 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Alabama Governor Republican Primary Election, 2010\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Bradley Byrne'''\n|137,451\n|27.89\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Robert Bentley'''\n|123,958\n|25.15\n|-\n|Republican\n|Tim James\n|123,792\n|25.12\n|-\n|Republican\n|Roy Moore\n|95,163\n|19.31\n|-\n|Republican\n|Bill Johnson\n|8,362\n|1.70\n|-\n|Republican\n|Charles Taylor\n|2,622\n|0.53\n|-\n|Republican\n|James Potts\n|1,549\n|0.31\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Alabama Governor Republican Primary runoff election, 2010\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Robert Bentley'''\n|261,233\n|56.09\n|-\n|Republican\n|Bradley Byrne\n|204,503\n|43.91\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Alabama 1st Congressional District Special Republican Primary Election, 2013\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Bradley Byrne'''\n|18,090\n|34.57\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Dean Young'''\n|12,011\n|22.95\n|-\n|Republican\n|Chad Fincher\n|8,177\n|15.63\n|-\n|Republican\n|Quin Hillyer\n|7,260\n|13.87\n|-\n|Republican\n|Wells Griffith\n|5,758\n|11.00\n|-\n|Republican\n|Daniel Dyas\n|391\n|0.75\n|-\n|Republican\n|Jessica James\n|391\n|0.75\n|-\n|Republican\n|Sharon Powe\n|184\n|0.35\n|-\n|Republican\n|David Thornton\n|72\n|0.14\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Alabama 1st Congressional District Special Republican Primary Runoff Election, 2013\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Bradley Byrne'''\n|38,150\n|52.50\n|-\n|Republican\n|Dean Young\n|34,534\n|47.50\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Alabama 1st Congressional District Special Election, 2013\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Bradley Byrne'''\n|36,042\n|71.00\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Burton LeFlore\n|14,968\n|29.00\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Alabama 1st Congressional District Election, 2014\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Bradley Byrne (inc.)'''\n|103,758\n|68.16\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Burton LeFlore\n|48,278\n|31.71\n|-\n|Write-ins\n|Write-ins\n|198\n|0.13\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Alabama 1st Congressional District Republican Primary Election, 2